docs.abstract: The movement is leaderless but not chaotic. It self-regulates even as it constantly reinvents itself.
docs.snippet: The movement is leaderless but not chaotic. It self-regulates even as it constantly reinvents itself.
docs.lead_paragraph: HONG KONG — The protests that have roiled Hong Kong for weeks, combining vast marches with small guerrilla operations of civil disobedience, are not the radical development that some say. They are a natural extension of protests past — an upgrade of the 2014 Umbrella Movement’s peaceful tactics of occupation. And they are a natural reaction to changing political circumstances, including a proposed bill that would allow, in effect, the extradition to mainland China of anyone in Hong Kong wanted by the Chinese authorities. The Chinese government’s power grab is accelerating the metabolism of the city’s protest movement.

headline.main: Hong Kong’s Protesters Are Resisting China With Anarchy and Principle
